    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Currently, Cython generates code to create constants (strings, tuples, code objects, â€¦) at module init time, using C-API calls. As an experimental [patch](https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/9320/files) by Facebook shows, the entire objects could be statically allocated and loaded from the C data segment instead. The [resulting C code](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python/cpython/267c93d61db9292921229fafd895b5ff9740b759/Python/frozenmodules.c) shows a nice example of code that Cython could generate as well.\r\n\r\nConstraints:\r\n- We need to keep the dynamic object creation, both as a fallback and to support PyPy.\r\n- This requires some adaptations across CPython versions, especially for Unicode strings. For that, we need to generate copies of the object structs and select them at C compile time via `PY_HEX_VERSION`.\r\n- In the easiest case, we could limit it to Py3.4+ for the beginning, as most object differences are between Py2 and Py3, so this would reduce the duplication.\r\n- It's unclear what to do about small integers and interned strings, since loading them from the data segment would prevent them from being singletons.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Another benefit is optimizing away unreachable code. For example, if you have something like:\r\n```cython\r\ncdef bool DEBUG = False;\r\n\r\ncdef do_something():\r\n    if DEBUG:\r\n         printf('Debug message\\n')\r\n```\r\nyou get something like:\r\n```c++\r\n#include <stdio.h>\r\n\r\nstatic bool __pyx_v__DEBUG;\r\n\r\nstatic int\r\n__pyx_pymod_exec_trace(PyObject *__pyx_pyinit_module)\r\n{\r\n    __pyx_v__DEBUG = 0;\r\n\r\n    return 0;\r\n}\r\n\r\nstatic void\r\ndo_something(void)\r\n{\r\n    int __pyx_t_1;\r\n\r\n    __pyx_t_1 = (__pyx_v__DEBUG != 0);\r\n    if (__pyx_t_1) {\r\n        printf(\"Debug message\\n\");\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf `__pyx_v__DEBUG` were initialized when it was defined, then an optimizing compiler (e.g., `gcc -O2`) would recognize that the `printf` could never be called and remove it entirely.",
